" data-medium-file="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-3-650x383.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-3.jpg" /><figcaption class="gallery-caption"> <span class="caption">The piece goes to whoever trimmed it last — in this case Carla. If both Bob and Carla had passed, Alice takes the piece.</span> <span class="credit">OLENA SHMAHALO</span> </figcaption></figure></li><li class="wrapper item-4" role="list-item" style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"><figure class="figure"><img decoding="async" width="650" height="383" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-4-650x383.jpg" class="attachment-medium size-medium" alt="" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="3131017" data-permalink="https://www.sciencenews.org/090923_cake-last-diminisher-4" data-orig-file="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-4.jpg" data-orig-size="681,401" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="090923_cake-last-diminisher-4" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p>;In round 2, any trimmings are added back to the remaining cake, and then the “divider-chooser” method for two people is used. Alice cuts the cake into what she thinks are two fair slices.&lt;/p>;
" data-medium-file="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-4-650x383.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-4.jpg" /><figcaption class="gallery-caption"> <span class="caption">In round 2, any trimmings are added back to the remaining cake, and then the “divider-chooser” method for two people is used. Alice cuts the cake into what she thinks are two fair slices.</span> <span class="credit">OLENA SHMAHALO</span> </figcaption></figure></li><li class="wrapper item-5" role="list-item" style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"><figure class="figure"><img decoding="async" width="650" height="383" src="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-5-650x383.jpg" class="attachment-medium size-medium" alt="" loading="lazy" data-attachment-id="3131018" data-permalink="https://www.sciencenews.org/090923_cake-last-diminisher-5" data-orig-file="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-5.jpg" data-orig-size="681,401" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="090923_cake-last-diminisher-5" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p>;Bob chooses his preferred slice. Alice gets the remaining slice. Everyone appears to be happy with their piece. But Carla, who exited the game early, could still think that Alice’s or Bob’s piece is better than hers.&lt;/p>;
" data-medium-file="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-5-650x383.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.sciencenews.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/090923_cake-last-diminisher-5.jpg" /><figcaption class="gallery-caption"> <span class="caption">Bob chooses his preferred slice. Alice gets the remaining slice. Everyone appears to be happy with their piece. But Carla, who exited the game early, could still think that Alice&#39;s or Bob&#39;s piece is better than hers.</span> <span class="credit">OLENA SHMAHALO</span></figcaption></figure></li></ol></div></div><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> Brams has called the last-diminisher method an elegant solution, and it guarantees that everyone judges their own piece to be at least as valuable as a fair share. But it&#39;s not perfect because it doesn&#39;t take envy into account. In both the lone-divider and last-diminisher approaches, a person who exits the game early may end up coveting a piece that is cut later in the game — even though they thought their piece was proportional. These algorithms are not what mathematicians call “envy-free,” which is another way to think about fairness.</p><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> There is another practical limitation to the last-diminisher method: With enough players, the cake that remains in later rounds might end up broken apart by a lot of slicing — or even reduced to crumbs. It&#39;s easy to see how a partygoer might not value that as highly as a whole piece.</p><h4 class="wp-block-heading" style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> Can cake cutting be free of envy?</h4><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> Since the debut of the last-diminisher method, cake cutting has fueled a small but mighty body of serious mathematics.</p><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> The 1960s brought a major step forward when mathematicians John Conway and John Selfridge, independently of each other, came up with a new cutting algorithm for three people. Unlike the work by Steinhaus and colleagues, the new recipe achieved both perceived proportionality and avoided any envy among the recipients.</p><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> An envy-free solution, in which no one covets another person&#39;s piece, is easy to achieve, points out computer scientist Haris Aziz of the University of New South Wales in Sydney. Just throw the entire cake away. “If you don&#39;t give anything to anybody, that&#39;s envy-free,” he says.</p><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> But if the cake lands in the rubbish bin, no one is happy. In Conway&#39;s and Selfridge&#39;s more pleasing scheme, Alice first divides the cake into three pieces she believes are of equal value. Then, Bob can trim one piece — at most — to create a two-way tie for the most valuable. (The trimmings are set aside.) Carla is left to choose among the three. Then the order reverses, and if Carla didn&#39;t choose the trimmed piece, Bob takes it. Alice gets the one that remains. The eaters then turn to the trimmings, following a similar iterative protocol of cutting, trimming and choosing.</p><div class="wp-block-sciencenews-content-sidebar" style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"><h3 class="wp-block-heading" style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> How to divide cake with no envy</h3><p style=";text-align:right;direction:rtl"> In a version of cake cutting for three people, each person — Alice, Bob and Carla — are guaranteed to feel that their piece represents 1/3 the total value of the cake. The method, named for John Selfridge and John Conway, also ensures that none of the cake eaters will be envious of another person&#39;s piece. The Selfridge-Conway procedure has been extended for any number people, but the cutting can last a very long time. </p><div
	class="container"
	data-component="slideshow"
